Dataset: PKDDâ€™99 Medical Data Set

A dataset was created using databases from the PKDDâ€™99 Discovery. The data was collected from university hospitals. Each patient came to the outpatient clinic for a collagen disease, and was reffered to the local hospitals by a doctor or general physician. Questions were formulated regarding patient data and itâ€™s relationship to thrombosis (see questions below). Relevent columns were selected and cleaned from the databases to create a new dataset stored in a CSV filed titled â€œthrombosis.csvâ€.


Analysis Questions

  1. Which autoimmune diseases are most associated to having thrombosis? Does this differ for moderate and severe cases?
  2. Which blood markers are most associated to thrombosis?
  3. How does cardiolipin antibody concentration relate to thrombosis?
  4. How does thrombosis effect women vs.Â men?


Insights & Findings


1: Diseases and Diagnoses Among Patients

This analysis begins with a curiosity in finding which diseases or conditions are common amongst those who have thrombosis and those who do not. In order to do this, the â€œDiagnosisâ€ columns in both tsumoto_a.csv and tsumoto_b.csv need to be parsed and cleaned. Many of the entries in this column were in varied formats, and abbreviations/shorthands were frequently used (for example pregnancy was recorded as both â€œPregâ€ and â€œPregnantâ€). A consistency was achevieved by putting the â€œDiagnosisâ€ column values into a table and visually identifying the abbreviations that should be grouped together. There were still nearly upwards of 100 diagnoses. Visualizing this many diagnoses would not be conducive to an interpretable visualization therefore the top 20 diagnoses were taken.


We first obtain the stacked bar chart seen on the left-hand side of the figure below. This displays the top 20 diagnoses of all patients by thrombosis status. SLE, SJS, and RA are the top 3 however, we see that prevalence of APS in thrombosis-positive patients is greater than SJS and RA in thrombosis-positive patients, even though SJS and RA are ranked higher. This plot is useful for getting a birdâ€™s eye view of the types of conditions the patients have. However, letâ€™s narrow our scope to only thrombosis patients (ie. only patients with positive thrombosis results).



We now obtain the stacked bar chart seen on the right-hand side of the figure above. SLE is still the top disease amongst thrombosis patients. However, the ordering of the remaining 19 has changed. Thrombosis patients seem to suffer more from APS and MCTD and less from RA than all patients. Another visual discovery is that diagnoses such as SLE, CNS, and even death are more common in severe cases of thrombosis. These stacked bar charts are side by side in the figure above to compare thrombosis patients from the non-thrombosis patients.


2: Blood Markers


Building from the insights above, we see that SLE is the most common diagnosis for thrombosis patients. SLE (also known as Lupus), is an autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks its own tissues. Symptoms include a reduced number of healthy red blood cells (anemia) and an increased risk of bleeding or blood clotting. The second most common diagnosis is APS which is increased risk of bloodclots. Thrombosis occurs when blood clots block veins or arteries so these make sense. MCTD is a rare disease however it is commonly seen in Lupus, and brain infarctions are caused by disrupted blood supply (ischemia) and restricted oxygen supply (hypoxia). For these reasons, the lab tests associated with blood are analyzed.


We begin by getting a big picture on which blood markers are related to thrombosis as well as which blood markers are associated to eachother. This is done in the correlation plot below. Because thrombosis has 3 factor levels (0 - Negative, 1 - Positive, 2 - Positive & severe), a special model matrix was created to account for this. Additionally, because many NAs existed across the different blood marker columns, the correlation matrix model only used complete observations (observations/rows with no NAs).



From the correlation plot we see that thrombosis is not strongly related to any one blood marker but it is most highly correlated to PT and FG. It is only negatively correlated with PLT and APTT. APTT is very highly negatively correlated to PT and the blood markers associated with red blood cell functioning such as HGB, HCT, and RBC are highly positively correlated.


We now wonder whether the blood marker results are different for thrombosis patients and non-thrombosis patients. Density plots were created for PT and FG since they had the highest positive correlation to thrombosis, as well as PLT and APTT since they have the highest (and only) negative correlations to thrombosis. Below are some interesting findings:



Looking at the density plot above, we visualize the distribution of APTT by thrombosis condition. Interestingly, the mean of the non-thrombosis is centered much farther away than expected. As indicated by the dashed line, the normal range should be < 45 but it is centered near the 90s. Those with moderate thrombosis are predominately in the normal range indicating they have lower APTT values. However, severe thrombosis has a bimodal distribution with both peaks above the normal range and 1 peak above the non-thrombosis patients. APTT evaluates a personâ€™s ability to appropriately form blood clots thus it makes sense that severe thrombosis cases are on the higher end of the APTT values.



Fibrinogen is a protein produced by the liver which helps stop bleeding by helping blood clots to form. When looking at the distributions for all 3 thrombosis factors, one might say that they are positioned similarly with centers just shy of being within the normal range. However, severe thrombosis patients have a much tighter distribution which leads us to believe that most of these patients have FG levels within that tight range unlike moderate thrombosis patients which have a much bigger spread. Their FG results are the most varied.


Because we are analyzing the blood markers through a â€œthrombosis vs.Â non-thrombosisâ€ lens, it would be interesting to see distribution of FG for all patients regardless of thrombosis. Do the larger and more varied results of the moderate thrombosis group pull the total distribution more into the normal range? According to the FG density plot below, it does, by pulling the distribution a bit to the right. It also does not have the same variation as the moderate thrombosis distribution seen in the plot above.



3: Antibodies


Collagen diseases are auto-immune diseases in which patientâ€™s anitbodies begin to attack their own body. We take a look at 3 of the most common anticardiolipin antibodies - Ig G, Ig M, and Ig A. These antibodies attacking the body are associated to issues with blood such as clotting. In order to visualize these antibodiesâ€™ effect on thrombosis, a side-by-side boxplot of the 3 anticardiolipin antibodies is shown below. Before this could happen, the data for each antibody was normalized. In the initial visualization, it was clear that all 3 antibodies had different ranges that could not be easily visualized side-by-side.



From the boxplot above, we see that anticardiolipin(aCl) IgA has the highest mean, and most of the observations are in a tighter range. For both aCl IgG and aCl IgM, the non-thrombosis patients are mainly concentrated around the mean. This boxplot made clear that there were many observations of patients who did not have thrombosis. In order to easily see the distributions of the antibodies and how it related to thrombosis, we obtain the plot below in which non-thrombosis patient data has been removed.



An interesting visual observation here was that for aCl IgG and aCl IgM, most of the higher-value outliers are moderate thrombosis patients. The severe thrombosis observations are mainly close to the mean and first quartile. In comparison to non-thrombosis patients, relatively more of those with thrombosis have higher values of IgG. IgG is an antibody most common in blood circulation which helps us understand this finding.


4: Effect on Sex


To get a high-level understanding of how thrombosis effects women vs.Â men, the relevent columns are subsetted, and melted so that they are suitable for the specific aesthetic mappings of the alluvium plot below. We discover a few things here:

  1. There are more female patients than male patients
  2. A small number of men are effected by severe thrombosis
  3. The proportion of women with severe thrombosis is close to the proportion of women with moderate thrombosis
  4. The proportion of men with severe thrombosis is smaller than the proportion of men with moderate thrombosis



Summary

From this analysis we now know that the top diagnosis associated to thrombosis is SLE. This was also the top diagnosis for all patients with collagen diseases. SLE is associated with an increased risk of bleeding or blood clotting. This led us to believe that blood markers may serve as an indication of thrombosis. None were very highly correlated to thrombosis however, many had different distributions for each thrombosis level. Perhaps certain fluctuations in the blood marker values over time can unearth more insight on thrombosis. Distributions of antibodies per thrombosis group also varied.


For this analysis, the back-to-back barplot in Figure 1 worked very well in showing the impact that non-thrombosis patients had on top diagnosis. Additionally, it was the launching pont for many of the questions that followed. The jitter-boxplots were maybe not the most ideal because each antibody had a different range of values. Also, representing the jitter so that all observations were not overshadowed by the â€œNegativeâ€ (non-thrombosis) group was a challenge.
